Legislature Size

Federal Republic with Very Large Legislature

The American government is a Federal Republic
with 535 members in its legislature. Executive elections are held every 4 years, the last of which occurred in 2012.

The United States' representative government has 19.4% of its seats filled by women. This is in line with than the female representation in government of other countries in Northern America (22.37%) and is in line with than female representation in governments around the world (19.30%).

Very High GDP per Capita, Staying Constant

Gross domestic product (GDP) measures the value of finished goods and services of a country.

The United States' GDP per capita is $55,836.80 which puts United States in the top 10th percentile in the world. A high GDP per capita suggests that economic productivity levels and standards of living are also amongst the highest in the world. On the national level, GDP is $17.9T which is 664 times higher than the world median ($27B).

In 2015, The United States' GDP grew 2.43% which is 3.15% higher for all countries in Northern America (-0.72%) and 0.49% lower than the median for all countries (2.92%).

Very High GNI per Capita

While GDP measures a country's overall economic output within its borders, gross national income, or GNI, accounts for net income from oversea investments. A foreign facility with American ownership, for example, would be accounted for in GNI, but not in GDP.

United States' GNI per capita is $54,960 which is 9.1 times higher than the world median ($6,010). On a nationwide level, GNI is $18.1T, which is 701 times higher than the world median ($25.9B).

Since United States' GNI is higher than its GDP, this suggests that United States has more foreign investments abroad than countries investing within its borders.

Slightly Low Unemployment Rate

United States' slightly low unemployment rate of 6.2% is 0.70% lower than the world average (6.90%). Low unemployment rates signify a healthy economy by generating high production and lessening strain on government support for the out-of-work population.

Of the unemployed in United States, 23% have faced continuous periods of unemployment that extend for a year or more. Males are more likely to encounter long-term unemployment at 23.7% compared to females at 22.2%.

High Trade Deficit

United States imports $2.78T in total goods and services, valued to be approximately 15.5% of the United States' GDP. This is 14.09% lower than all countries in Northern America (29.59%) and 28.86% lower than all countries (44.36%).

Export of goods and services total $2.26T or value roughly 12.6% of the United States' GDP. Compared to other countries in Northern America, United States exports are 18.98% lower than the region median (31.54%) and at the global level 22.40% lower than all countries (34.96%).

In aggregate, the value of imports and exports make up 28.06 % of GDP of the American GDP. Net exports indicate a trade deficit of $521B, indicating an outflow of domestic currency to foreign markets.

Consistently Easy to do Business

United States is the 7th easiest country to do business in out of 189 surveyed countries, according to the World Bank's Ease of Doing Business rankings. The index averages 10 topics covered in the survey ranging in access to credit to finding employees and starting a business.

According to the index, United States is one of the easiest places to do business in 2015, and has not changed its rank significantly since last year.

Very Large Total Population with Low Population Density

At 321M, the United States' population is 4,928 times larger than the Northern America median (65181) and 60 times larger than the world median (5.37M). With a population density of 35.14 people per sq km, the United States is 51.1 times less dense than the world median (86.2 people per sq km).

In 2015, United States had a population growth rate of 0.78% which is 0.43% lower than the world median (1.2%).

Primarily Urban

Rural and urban areas are defined by national statistical offices and normalized by the U.N. Population Division.

The majority of the United States' population live in urban areas. As of 2015, 82% of the population is living in an urban area which is approximately the same level as other countries in Northern America (84%). This is 23.0% higher than other countries around the world (59%). Presently, the urban population is growing at a rate of 0.99%, 0.6 times slower than the world median (1.66%)

The rural population makes up 18.38% of the total population in the United States and is currently declining at a rate of 0.14%

Low Birth Rate and Average Death Rate

The birth rate accounts for the annual number of live births. At 13 births per 1,000 people, United States's birth rate is about the same as the Northern America median (12 births per 1,000 people) and has 5 fewer births per 1,000 people than the world median (18 births per 1,000 people).

The death rate accounts for the annual number of deaths. In 2015, the death rate was 8 deaths per 1,000 people which is is about the same as the world median (7 deaths per 1,000 people). United States's low birth rate is significantly higher than its death rate which may contribute to a steady increase is slightly higher than its death rate which may contribute to a steady increase of its population.

High Educational Attainment

To assess the level of educational attainment in countries around the world, the U.N. Development Program created the Education Index which calculates the mean years of schooling and expected years of schooling in 187 countries. According to the index in 2013, the United States is amongst the best educated countries in the world at a value of 0.89 out of 1. This would make the United States 0.24 points higher than the world median (0.65).

The United States has an adult literacy rate of 86% which is 8.02% lower than the world median (94.02%)

Education Begins at an Average Age, and is of Average Length

Most American students enter primary school at 6 years old, about the same age as the world average (6 years old). Secondary school in United States begins at 12 years old, about the same age as the world average (12 years old).

For American students, schooling lasts approximately 12 years, with primary and secondary education taking up equal lengths. Compared to students worldwide, American students are in school about the same length as the world median (12 years).

Land Area

Very Large Country with Long Coastline

The United States' total land area is 9.15M square kilometers or 3.53M square miles. This is 4.4M square kilometers larger than the median sized country in Northern America (4.75M square kilometers) and 9.05M square kilometers larger than median sized country worldwide (96,893 square kilometers).

Coastline accounts for the total boundary between the land area and the sea. The United States' has a coastline the length of 19,924 kilometers.

High Forest Cover

An area is considered to be forested if at least 5 meters of land has natural or planted trees. Trees used in agricultural production and urban parks or gardens are excluded.


33.84% or approximately 3,047,880 square kilometers of the United States' land area is covered by forests. This is about the same amount of forest area as other countries in Northern America (26.92%). On a global scale, United States has 1.86% more forest cover than global median (31.98%).

Major Contributor of CO₂ Emissions

CO₂ emissions account for the carbon dioxide that was produced during the consumption of fuels, fossil fuel burning, and the manufacture of cement.

Americans emit 16.4 metric tons of CO₂ per capita a year, or roughly 5,186,168 kilotonne as a country. Compared to other countries in Northern America, United States emits 4.6 metric tons per capita more than the region median (11.8 metric tons per capita).

On a global scale, The United States emits 13.6 metric tons per capita more than the world median (2.8 metric tons per capita).

High Level of Conservation Effort

Extremely High Energy Consumption

General electric power consumption in the United States is 12,988 kWh per capita. This is 1,266 kWH per capita less electricity consumption for countries in Northern America (14,254 kWh per capita) and 10,457 kWH per capita more electricity consumption for countries around the world (2,531 kWh per capita)

Fossil fuel is the most common sources of energy consumption in the United States with 83.26% of its energy derived from coal, oil, petroleum, and natural gas products. Alternative and nuclear energy make up 12.12% of its energy consumption followed by combustible renewables and waste energy use at 4.43%.

Low Use of Renewable Energy

Renewable energy sources such as geothermal, solar, and wind make up 6.86% of the United States' electricity production. This means the United States produces 2.1% more electricity from renewable energy sources compared to other countries in Northern America (4.77%) and produces 1.7% more electricity from oil and coal compared to other countries globally (65.84%). Additionally, 6.05% of the electricity production is derived from hydroelectric power plants such as dams.

67.5% of the United States' electricity production is derived from oil, gas, and coal sources. The United States produces 23.1% more electricity from oil and coal compared to other countries Northern America (44.43%) and is in line with the median level of electricity produced from oil and coal for countries globally (65.84%).

Long Life Expectancy

Life expectancy at birth accounts for the number of years a newborn infant would live under prevailing conditions. Americans can expect to live 79 years which is about the same as the region median (80 years). Globally, life expectancies in the United States is 6 years longer than the world median (73 years).

In the United States, women can expect to live longer than men by 5 years. Life expectancy of females is 82 years while the life expectancy of males is 77 years.

Many Live to 65 Years Old

On average, 84.6% of Americans live to 65 years old, about as many as the region median (87.24%) and 6.93% more than the world median (77.67%).

Women in the United States have a higher chance of living to 65 years old than men. In general, women have a 88.2% likelihood to live to least 65 years old while men have a 81.0% chance.

Very Low Tuberculosis Incidences

Tuberculosis incidences account for the estimated number of new and relapse tuberculosis cases in a given year. An estimated 3 out of every 100,000 Americans are afflicted with tuberculosis, in line with than the Northern America median (4 cases per 100,000 people) and 46 cases per 100,000 people less the world median (49 cases per 100,000 people). Of these, 83% cases are successfully treated.

Most Children Vaccinated

A child is considered to be immunized from DPT (diphtheria, pertussis, and tetanus) after receiving three doses of vaccine. In 2015, 95% of American children ages 12-23 months received the DPT vaccination. This is 2.00% more than Northern America median (93.00%) and 2.00% more than the global median (93.00%).

As of 2015, 92% of American children in the same age group were vaccinated for measles. Compared to the median measles vaccination rate for countries in Northern America, American children are 1.00% more likely to be vaccinated (91.00%) and on a global level, the vaccination rate is in line with than world median (93.00%).

Sports

Olympic Medal Counts

Total Medals (in all Olympics)
Total Medals (per Million People)
Very High Number of Olympic Medals

In the history of the Olympic Games, United States has won 2802 medals the most medals by any country. The United States has participated in 49 Olympic games, averaging 57.2 medals each Olympic games.

Of the medals, most are gold medals which make up approximately 40% of the total medals. Silver medals account for 32% of the medals, followed by bronze medals at 28%.

Like most countries, the United States has won most of its medals during the Summer Games. The United States has won about 9 times as many medals during the summer games compared to the winter games.

Very Low Military Spending

United States spends 3.32% of its GDP on military expenditures. These expenditures include current and capital expenditures on armed forces, including peacekeeping forces. This is 1.81% higher than the world median of 1.51%.

Though military spending encompasses 3.32% of United States' GDP, it encompasses 15.31% of the central government's expenditure.

Military Branches and Regulations

Military Branches:

United States Armed Forces: US Army, US Navy (includes Marine Corps), US Air Force, US Coast Guard; note - Coast Guard administered in peacetime by the Department of Homeland Security, but in wartime reports to the Department of the Navy (2013)

Conscription Regulations:

18 years of age (17 years of age with parental consent) for male and female voluntary service; no conscription; maximum enlistment age 42 (Army), 27 (Air Force), 34 (Navy), 28 (Marines); service obligation 8 years, including 2-5 years active duty (Army), 2 years active (Navy), 4 years active (Air Force, Marines); DoD is eliminating prohibitions restricting women from assignments in units smaller than brigades or near combat units (2013)
